# The Letter by the Culvert

Rain had been falling since breakfast, the kind of rain that made every fence post look older and every road feel longer.

Mira, a fox with a satchel full of *borrowed library books*, cut across the orchard because she was late and because being late felt better than turning back.

At the edge of the field she found a letter pinned beneath a stone, the paper gone soft but the ink still **stubborn**.

> If this reaches anyone kind, please carry it to the red house
> beyond the bridge. My father waits there every Thursday.

She looked up at the bridge, then at the river, then at the
letter again as if it might choose its own owner.

In her satchel she had only three useful things:

- a loaf wrapped in wax paper
- a dry scarf
- a brass key she had never managed to throw away

The bridge planks trembled under her weight, but the river
below was louder than fear and colder than doubt.

---

## The Red House

The man who opened the door had the careful face of someone
who had been disappointed often enough to do it politely.

Mira held out the letter. For a moment he did not move.

Then he laughed once, softly, and pressed a hand to his eyes.

"I wrote this to my brother," he said. "Twenty years ago."

They drank tea while the storm walked across the roof.
When Mira left, the rain had thinned to a silver mist,
and the road home seemed shorter than before.
